recordings.rmk: The recording was high-pass filtered at 3000 Hz with a roll-off of 12 dB/Hz to eliminate road noise. The bird was perched on a barbed wire fence and was calling in response to aggression from another bird. The other bird was only seen poorly and could have been another Marsh Wren. The bird calling in this recording was moving away from me as time progressed, so later calls are from farther away. This call appears to be the kek-call. It's unknown whether subspecies in Kittitas county are C. p. pulverius or browningi/paludicola, particularly individuals found during the Winter. The only other species present were Song Sparrow and Fox Sparrow (XC396200). Recording made on an handheld Olympus LS-10 linear PCM recorder.
